In the traditional approach to development there were three ingredients : First , transferring resources from rich countries in northern poor countries in the south , accompanied with prescriptions for reforms .
The second , the development institutions that made these resources were not really transparent , with small transparency for what they funded or the results they achieved .
And third , the involvement in developing countries was in a short framework of government elites with small contact with the citizens , which is actually the final goal of development aid .
Today , each of these components is starting to change because of dramatic changes in the global environment .
Open knowledge , open aid , open government , which together , represents three key changes that change the nature of development and that gives hope about the problems I &apos;ve seen in Uganda and Bahar .
The first key change is open knowledge .
The developing countries today don &apos;t just have to accept solutions that are replaced by the United States , Europe or the World Bank .
